JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand was firmer in early trade on Wednesday, adding to gains notched up the previous session after the country&#8217;s top court said it would consider whether a motion of no confidence against President Jacob Zuma should be taken by secret ballot. The rand traded 0.4% stronger at 13.7675 against the dollar as of 0650 GMT.South Africa&#8217;s top court said on Tuesday it would consider whether a motion of no confidence against Zuma should be taken by secret ballot, as pressure mounted on him to resign after a controversial cabinet reshuffle.&#8220;A secret ballot would significantly change the probability of but certainly not guarantee the motion passing,&#8221; RMB Global Markets said in a note.Stocks were likely to open higher at 0700 GMT, with futures up 0.4%.Government bonds firmed, the yield on the benchmark 2026 instrument was down 4.5 basis points to 8.910%.